occurrences.line_text: On whom she list, and did great liking sheowe,
Which who so list looke backe to former ages,
Ne list I for reuenge prouoke new fight,
That she your loue list loue another knight,
List not to hearke, but made this faire denyall;
She list discouer, and of goodly stature;
Then entred Cambell first into the list,
When who so list to fight, may fight his fill,
Her list no longer in that place abide;
And rend a sunder quite, if he thereto list striue.
And at his will may whom he list restore,
And whom he list reserue, to be afflicted more.
All which who list by tryall to assay,
In milder tearmes, as list them to deuise:
Yet though he neuer list to me relent,
He where he list goes loose, and laughes at me.
For who so list into the heauens looke,
When so he list in wrath lift vp his steely brand.
For all we haue is his: what he list doe, he may.
And them against came all that list to giust,
Shapt like a horses shoe, who list to seeke it there.
As thing at randon left, to whom he list.
Vp to her ham, but when she list, it raught
He list no lenger to vse lothfull speach,
But go, which way they list, their guide they haue forlore.
Till that th'offended heauens list to lowre
Behinde, beside, before, as he it list apply.
Whereto she euer list to make her hardy flight.
To passe them ouer, where them list to tell:
She hidden was, and sought her so long, as him list.
And sent me, where him list, instructed for to bee.
His name (quoth he) if that thou list to learne,
What euer formes ye list thereto apply,
Whether ye list him traine in cheualry,
That if ye list to haste a litle more,
Let them that list, their lucklesse lot deplore;
Ne list the Knight the powre thereof assay,
To be captiu'd, and handled as he list,
But let them loue that list, or liue or die;
Me list not die for any louers doole:
Ne list me leaue my loued libertie,
To pitty him that list to play the foole:
That if ye list haue liberty, ye may,
To them, that list, the worlds gay showes I leaue,
And all the day, to what I list, I doe attend.
And long while after, whilest him list remaine,
But whom they of them selues list so to grace.
The same againe if now ye list to haue,
And when her listed, she could fawne and flatter;
Then listen Lordings, if ye list to weet
But yet, if please ye listen to my lore,
Came to the open hall, to listen whose
Oft listening if he mote her heare againe;
The field with listes was all about enclos'd,
Broke vp the listes, their armes away to rend;
At last arriuing by the listes side,
Soone as he did within the listes appeare,
And to his doome with listfull eares did both attend.
Which she long listning, softly askt againe
Ne euer wont in field, ne in round lists to fight.
In equall lists they should the morrow next it fight.
Well could he tourney and in lists debate,
All arm'd to point, and first the Lists did enter:
The Lists were closed fast, to barre the rout
Litae, by him begot in loues delight,
When in so high an obiect they do lite,
What fortune to the Briton Prince did lite,
Yet would not let her lite, nor rest a little stead.
The stroke vpon his shield so heauie lites,
As if his lungs and lites were nigh a sunder brast.
A litle glooming light, much like a shade,
And on his litle winges the dreame he bore
Him litle answerd th'angry Elfin knight;
Then sighing soft, I learne that litle sweet
But in vaine glorious frayes he litle did delight.
What if some litle paine the passage haue,
The faithfull knight now grew in litle space,
And eke a litle Hermitage thereby,
A litle path, that was both steepe and long,
And after litle rest, gan him desire,
And of three furlongs does but litle lacke;
Halfe dead through feare, her litle babe reuyld,
Thy litle hands embrewd in bleeding brest
His litle hands, and tender ioynts embrew;
Full litle weenest thou, what sorrowes are
Yet still the litle hands were bloudie seene;
So long they traueiled with litle ease,
One thought their cheare too litle, th'other thought too mutch.
But of her loue too lauish (litle haue she thancke.)
But litle may such guile thee now auaile,
Though otherwise it did him litle harme:
A litle Gondelay, bedecked trim
That like a litle forrest seemed outwardly.
About her litle frigot, therein making way.
My litle boat can safely passe this perilous bourne.
Emongst wide waues set, like a litle nest,
Me litle needed from my right way to haue straid.
At last him to a litle dore he brought,
Betwixt them both was but a litle stride,
And eke emongst them litle Cupid playd
A litle boy did on him still attend,
Which with a staffe, all full of litle snags
Full litle wanted, but he had him slaine,
By whom a litle skippet floting did appeare.
He bore a crowned litle Ermilin,
Beldame, your words doe worke me litle ease;
With great deuotion, and with litle zeale:
The cause some say is this: A litle while
Some litle life his feeble sprites emong;
Litle she weend, that loue he close concealed;
And in her litle loues stead, which was strayd,
A litle smoke, whose vapour thin and light,
Who finding litle leasure her to wooe,
Her sharpe rebuke full litle did esteeme;
Of which he now did very litle fayle,
For litle good of him is to be got,
She litle answer'd him, but lightly did aggrate.
Adowne their sides like litle riuers stremed,
Whence litle lust he had to rise againe.
And litle prays'd his labours euill speed,
And if by fortune any litle nap
Some litle whispering, and soft groning sound.
And with a litle golden chaine about it bound.
Would flit a litle forward, and then stay,
A litle cotage farre away they spide,
Bearing a litle Dwarfe before his steed,
That the other litle gained by the lone,
So litle did they hearken to her sweet beheast.
Were cowards knowne, and litle count did hold,
Of litle much, of foes she maketh frends,
A flocke of litle loues, and sports, and ioyes,
The which for sparing litle cost or paines,
Congealed litle drops, which doe the morne adore.
Yet litle losse it were, and mickle thanke,
That as his head he gan a litle reare
Yet all the wrongs could not a litle right downe lay.
As fortune fell; yet litle lost or wonne:
Of both beloued well, but litle frended;
That of his shape appear'd no litle moniment.
And passing litle further, commen were,
Mongst which crept litle Angels through the glittering gleames.
Seemed those litle Angels did vphold
And much to gaine, a litle for to yield;
Vpon the which she litle spinnes, but spils,
The litle babe did loudly scrike and squall,
The litle babe, sweet relickes of his pray;
And euery litle limbe he searcht around,
And euermore his louely litle spoile
This litle babe, of sweete and louely face,
And hauing ouer it a litle wept,
That if ye list to haste a litle more,
And ere that litle while they ridden had,
Vnto a litle groue not farre asyde,
He mote perceiue a litle dawning sight
And to the litle cots, where shepherds lie
Vpon a litle hillocke she was placed
And streight vnto her litle flocke did fare:
The which doth litle craue contented to abyde.
So taught of nature, which doth litle need
The litle that I haue, growes dayly more
And other, that hath litle, askes no more,
But in that litle is both rich and wise.
Did litle whit regard his courteous guize,
Or litle sparrowes, stolen from their nest,
Old loue is litle worth when new is more prefard.
Litle for him to haue one silly lasse:
To sparke out litle beames, like starres in foggie night.
To keepe their flockes for litle hyre and chepe:
And with their litle stings right felly fare;
The litle babe, to take thereof a sight.
Vpon the litle brest like christall bright,
She mote perceiue a litle purple mold,
Yet left not quite, but drew a litle space
That litle Infant had, which forth she kest,
The litle purple rose, which thereon grew,
A little lowly Hermitage it was,
In trauell to and froe: a little wyde
Arriued there, the little house they fill,
Legions of Sprights, the which like little flyes
That much was worne, but therein little red,
For of deuotion he had little care,
Vnto the woods, to see her little sonne;
Yet outwardly some little comfort shewes:
At euery little breath, that vnder heauen is blowne.
But in the same a little grate was pight,
She him obayd, and turnd a little wyde.
A little backward for his best defence,
Death were too little paine for such a foule despight.
Through midst thereof a little riuer rold,
The little babe vp in his armes he hent;
Thou little wotest, what this right hand can:
Now little gan to swell, and being tide,
The fire of sparkes, the weede of little seede,
The little barke vnto the shore to draw,
He lookt a little further, and espyde
That like a little lake it seemd to bee;
A little leaue vnto a rusticke Muse
So that at last a little creeping sleepe
Vnder a rocke that lyes a little space
And in the midst a little riuer plaide
Her little sonne, the winged god of loue,
A little valley, subiect to the same,
A little cottage, built of stickes and reedes
A little boate lay houing her before,
Full little weened I, that chastitee
To fly for succour to a little shed,
A little off, his shield was rudely throwne,
The whiles her foolish garde, that little knew
That little drops empurpled her faire brest.
Now growen great, at first of little seedes,
He little answer'd, but in manly heart
Who lookt a little vp at that his speech,
Are quite deuourd, and brought to nought by little bits?
They spide a little cottage, like some poore mans nest.
And fast beside a little brooke did pas
That any little blow on her did light,
And manly limbs endur'd with little care
All little Riuers, which owe vassallage
As that ye would for little leaue the same,
But in my way a little here beyond
That he of little things made reckoning light,
Now with faire words; but words did little good,
But like a little Mount of small degree;
To whom but little dowre allotted was;
And then my loue (though now it little skill,)
And little had for his excuse to say,
For little lust had she to talke of ought,
Not farre away, but little wide by West,
My life now to, for which a little whyle
And armes had borne, but little good could finde,
For little bootes against him hand to reare.
Wilt giue thy beard, though it but little bee?
It to performe: so after little stay,
By which a little Hermitage there lay,
And nigh thereto a little Chappell stoode,
Small was his house, and like a little cage,
Mote easie be supprest with little thing:
Yet would not let her lite, nor rest a little stead.
Their dwelling in a little Island was,
A little well is lent, that gaineth more withall.
A little mayde, the which ye chylded tho;
(Quoth he) as wretched, and liu'd in like paine.
To them, that liu'd therein in state forlorne;
Ne yet Mathusalem, though longest liu'd;
He liu'd, returning to his natiue place,
So liu'd they euer after in like sin,
In whom he liu'd a new, of former life depriued.
For he liu'd all on rauin and on rape
And pitty much his plight, that liu'd like outcast thrall.
So chast and loyall liu'd, but she would striue
They liu'd together long without debate:
Ne any liu'd on ground, that durst withstand
In which he liu'd alone, like carelesse bird in cage.
That euer liu'd, and th'onely glory of his might.
That Pastorell yet liu'd, but all the rest
Who whiles he liu'de, was called proud Sans foy,
Whither the soules do fly of men, that liue amis.
Where they should liue in woe, & die in wretchednesse.
A liue or dead: and forward forth doth pas,
Yet liue perforce in balefull darkenesse bound?
Now in your powre, to let her liue, or dye.
But he should die, who merites not to liue?
The man that would not liue, but earst lay at deathes dore.
For if he liue, that hath you doen despight,
As bound by them to liue in liues despight,
Long maist thou liue, and better thriue withall,
Liue thou, and to thy mother dead attest,
And losse of loue, to her that loues to liue,
Then to him said, Liue and allegaunce owe,
Thou that doest liue in later times, must wage
And vnto all that liue in high degree,
And to those brethren said, Rise rise by liue,
The trespasse still doth liue, albe the person die.
I liue this day, and see my foes subdewd,
Donwallo dyde (for what may liue for ay?)
Long mayst thou Glorian liue, in glory and great powre.
Let all that liue, hereby be counselled,
To liue in thraldome of his fathers foe;
I feared loue: but they that loue do liue,
Of all things, that are borne to liue and die,
And sendeth forth to liue in mortall state,
Therefore needs mote he liue, that liuing giues to all.
To all faire Ladies, that doe liue on ground.
Yet has full large to liue, and spend at libertie.
Tho when againe he him bethought to liue,
Must not here thinke to liue: for life is wretchednesse.
Yet both in flowres do liue, and loue thee beare,
This doe and liue, else die vndoubtedly.
The meed of them that loue, and do not liue amisse.
Long may you liue in health and happie state.
What time she vsd to liue in wiuely sort;
But die or liue for nought he would vpstand
And now become to liue a Ladies thrall,
For on the spoile of women he doth liue,
Of time, did liue then like an innocent,
Th'Elysian fields, and liue in lasting blesse,
In bands of friendship, there did liue for euer,
And let him liue vnlou'd, or loue him selfe alone.
Then let mee liue, as louers ought to do,
They liue, they die, like as he doth ordaine,
I trust a liue, sith I thee fostred first;
For if I liue till those ten daies haue end,
The wretchedst Dame, that liue this day on ground;
I giuen haue, liue in reproch and scorne;
And onely suffred him this wretched life to liue.
And so would euer liue, and loue her owne delight.
But let them loue that list, or liue or die;
There dwelt a saluage nation, which did liue
To sad decay, that might contented liue.
As graunt me liue in like condition;
And in this quiet make you safer liue.
That neuer vsde to liue by plough nor spade,
That euer I did liue, this day to see,
That yond same is your daughter sure, which yet doth liue.
To be the fairest wight, that liued yit;
When best shall be to them, that liued best:
To proue he liued ill, that did thus foully dye.
The guilt, which if he liued had thus long,
The wisest men, I weene, that liued in their ages.
By hunting and by spoiling liued then;
Yet whilest they liued none did euer see
It would haue liued, and reuiued eft;
Whilest here on earth she liued mortallie.
For that Osyris, whilest he liued here,
As any one, that liued in his daies,
And liued long in peace and loue entyre,
Plaine signes in him of life and liuelihead.
Left thee for portion of thy liuelihed,
And former liuelod fayle, she left me quight,
And of lesse liuelood and hability,
So liuely, and so like in all mens sight,
His blessed body spoild of liuely breath,
And liuely breath her sad brest did forsake,
Did labour liuely to expresse the same,
Full liuely is the semblaunt, though the substance dead.
Yet liuely vigour rested in his mind,
Of which some seemd with liuely iollitee,
And form'd so liuely in each perfect part
Who can it doe more liuely, or more trew,
Which in that cloth was wrought, as if it liuely grew.
Chaunged thy liuely cheare, and liuing made thee dead?
And soyle which did deforme their liuely hew;
So liuely and so like, that many it mistooke.
That like a liuely sanguine it seem'd to the eye.
Daunst liuely, and her face did with a Lawrell shade.
Did liuely seeme to tremble, wheh she saw
For griefe whereof, ye mote haue liuely seene
All which in that faire arras was most liuely writ.
So liuely and so like, that liuing sence it fayld.
By liuely actions he gan bewray
Gan fade, and liuely spirits deaded quight:
What mote ye weene, if the trew liuely-head
Croscuts the liuer with internall smart,
As of her owne by liuerey and seisin,
His deadly wounds within my liuers swell,
Backe to the world, bad liuers to torment:
Silly old man, that liues in hidden cell,
That such a cursed creature liues so long a space.
He liues, that shall him pay his dewties last,
How mortgaging their liues to Couetise,
And liues he yet (said he) that wrought this act,
He liues, (quoth he) and boasteth of the fact,
As bound by them to liue in liues despight,
As if their liues had in his hand beene gaged;
To shed your liues on ground? wo worth the man,
Whose liues, it seemed, whilome there were shed,
For losse of thousand liues, to dye at her desire.
If that your liues ye loue, as meete ye should;
Liues any, that you hath thus ill apaid?
Whence all that liues, does borrow life and light,
Liues ought, that to her linage may compaire,
Yet liues his memorie, though carcas sleepe in rest.
That liues, pertaines in charge particulare,
But who that liues, is left to waile his losse:
Liues none this day, that may with her compare
They three be dead with shame, the Squire liues with renowne.
He liues, but takes small ioy of his renowne;
We mortall wights, whose liues and fortunes bee
For all that liues, is subiect to that law:
There now he liues in euerlasting ioy,
She with him liues, and hath him borne a chyld,
Whose fruitlesse liues were vnder furrow sowne,
In sewing deeds of armes, my liues and labours end.
Yet can he neuer dye, but dying liues,
That her liues Lord and patrone of her health
doth lengthen her sonnes liues.
The perilous present stownd, in which their liues were set.
That so their liues might be prolonged late.
That both their liues may likewise be annext
Or how their liues were eekt, she did not tell;
That could her purchase with his liues aduentur'd gage.
Thereby to make their loues beginning, their liues end.
With which their liues thou lanchedst long afore,
That liues a loathed life, and wishing cannot die.
Enfolding said, And liues yet Amyas?
He liues (quoth he) and his ï¿½mylia loues.
Out of their wretched corses, and their liues depriue.
Whose liues although decay'd, yet loues decayed neuer.
Liues still: and to this feast with Neptunes seed was dight.
I rather chose to die in liues despight,
They trode, and on the ground their liues did strow,
That liues on earth; but vnto those alone
And him adoring as her liues deare Lord,
In Cornewale, till that he through liues despeire
To leape into the same after our liues end.
Then for to die with her, and his liues threed to breake.
Why liuest thou, dead dog, a lenger day,
And liuest thou my daughter now againe?
Or let him die at ease, that liueth here vneath?
Fairer and nobler liueth none this howre,
There now he liueth in eternall blis,
To whom he thus; She liueth sure and sound;
Then which a prouder Lady liueth none:
And dead as liuing euer him ador'd:
The fearefull Dwarfe:) this is no place for liuing men.
His dwelling is, by which no liuing wight
That liuing creature mote it not abide;
Banisht from liuing wights, our wearie dayes we waste.
Till we be bathed in a liuing well;
When all this speech the liuing tree had spent,
Though faire as euer liuing wight was faire,
Yet neuer shew of liuing wight espyde;
In liuing Princes court none euer knew
For she was wondrous faire, as any liuing wight.
Yet chylde ne kinsman liuing had he none
Does care for looke of liuing creatures eye.
These eyes did see that knight both liuing and eke ded.
That it would pitty any liuing eie.
His liuing like saw neuer liuing eye,
His liuing like saw neuer liuing eye,
All liuing wightes in might of magicke spell:
What worlds delight, or ioy of liuing speach
Where neuer foot of liuing wight did tread,
Whose gates he found fast shut, ne liuing wight
Where liuing creature none he did espye;
With all his powre, to weet, if liuing wight
More vgly shape yet neuer liuing creature saw.
From liuing eyes her open shame to hide,
That rules mens wayes, and rules the thoughts of liuing wight.
Till liuing moysture into smoke do flow,
To kindle loue in euery liuing brest;
Ne liuing man like words did euer heare,
Yf liuing man mote worthy be, to be her liefe.
A wide way made to let forth liuing breath.
Or let him die, that loatheth liuing breath?
All is but lost, that liuing we bestow,
But that same end, which euery liuing wight
Did burne with wrath, and sparkled liuing fyre;
So wondrous force, from hand of liuing wight;
His wearie foe into that liuing well,
Ne liuing wight would haue him life behot:
The face of earth, and wayes of liuing wight,
For neuer liuing man, I weene, so sore
Or false or trew, or liuing or else dead,
Sith none, that breatheth liuing aire, does know,
With liuing eye more faire was neuer seene,
Sith heauen thee deignes to hold in liuing state,
Of liuing bloud yet in her veynes did hop;
That at the last she gan to breath out liuing aire.
Which feedes each liuing plant with liquid sap,
In her faire eyes two liuing lamps did flame,
And much ashamd, that stroke of liuing arme
Was giuen all to lust and loose liuing,
In his owne flesh, and make way to the liuing spright.
And Shame his vgly face did hide from liuing eye.
That liuing eye before did neuer see:
On earth like neuer grew, ne liuing wight
For lenger time, then that, no liuing wight
So backe againe, him brought to liuing light.
Whose liuing hands immortalizd his name.
But leaue these relicks of his liuing might,
And keepes in couerts close from liuing wight,
For they of liuing fire most subtilly
Faire Helena, the fairest liuing wight;
Ne euer land beheld, ne liuing wight,
Of huge Sea monsters, such as liuing sence dismayd.
Is sweet, and pleasing vnto liuing sense,
Such as attonce might not on liuing ground,
For all that pleasing is to liuing eare,
If pourtrayd it might be by any liuing art.
But liuing art may not least part expresse,
But if in liuing colours, and right hew,
Yet tract of liuing creatures none they found,
Whose soueraine beautie hath no liuing pere,
For liuing wit, I weene, cannot display
Whose prowesse paragon saw neuer liuing wight.
Chaunged thy liuely cheare, and liuing made thee dead?
Nor man it is, nor other liuing wight;
In liuing brests, ykindled first aboue,
Which through the earth haue spred their liuing prayse,
That of no liuing wight he mote be found,
Then euer him before or after liuing wight.
Of mortall Syre, or other liuing wight,
That liuing him in all actiuity
Nor so fowle outrage doen by liuing men:
A lesson too too hard for liuing clay,
That euer liuing eye I weene did see;
Prouidence heauenly passeth liuing thought,
Saw neuer liuing eye more heauy sight,
That greatest Princes liuing it mote well delight.
